Gene, sure evolutionary algorithms have been applied to both open-e=
nded and creative endeavors for many years before novelty search.  In fact =
both our introductory papers on novelty search (ALIFE-08 and ECJ 11) includ=
e sections that explicitly cite prior work in open-ended evolution as an in=
spiration for novelty search.  There is no doubt that they share many princ=
iples.



Creative systems such as interactive evolution also share many pr=
inciples with novelty search, which is the inspiration for the publication =
at the root of this discussion thread.  So certainly we don&#39;t want to imply=
 that novelty search is the first to explore open-endedness or creativity i=
n evolution (much of my own work is even in creative evolutionary systems o=
utside novelty search).  In fact, we view novelty search as a complement to=
 the work in this area.  Diversity-preservation-mechanisms (such as speciat=
ion) and coevolution also relate to novelty search in various ways.



Howe=
ver, novelty search is the only generic (i.e. domain-general) evolutionary =
algorithm we know of that explicitly rewards phenotypic novelty and only no=
velty with no other criteria and no awareness of the objective whatsoever (=
many such prior algorithms combine objective criteria with a drive towards =
diversity).  To our knowledge it is also the first time that such an open-e=
nded approach was used to show that many problems considered objective can =
be transformed into non-objective problems that are actually solved better =
without an objective (which remains a controversial yet useful discussion p=
oint).  



If you would like to share another algorithm that is similar th=
en that&#39;s great (the book you cited is a survey of many systems, and I don&#39;=
t know of a specific example in that book that works like novelty search). =
 Of course, after four years of publication reviews I would be surprised to=
 see something with the same exact mechanism that our reviewers did not cat=
ch, but it&#39;s a big world and you never know.  However, I would not be surpr=
ised to see many related ideas - of course open-ended evolution and creativ=
e evolutionary systems share much of the same inspiration as novelty search=
.  Our hope was in effect to distill the core essence of such systems into =
the simplest possible heuristic to make its study and applicability as easy=
 and universal as possible.



It&#39;s probably also useful to note that the m=
otivation for starting this discussion for me was not to argue that novelty=
 search is &quot;superior.&quot;  Rather I think its generality and simplicity make i=
t a useful device for investigating the impact of our field&#39;s longstanding =
loyalty to objective-driven algorithms and evaluation standards, in particu=
lar in domains that are considered &quot;objective.&quot;  If other approaches also c=
ontribute to that discussion then all the better!



