Gene, sure evo=
lutionary algorithms have been applied to both open-ended and creative ende=
avors for many years before novelty search.  In fact both our introductory =
papers on novelty search (ALIFE-08 and ECJ 11) include sections that explic=
itly cite prior work in open-ended evolution as an inspiration for novelty =
search.  There is no doubt that they share many principles.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Creati=
ve systems such as interactive evolution also share many principles with no=
velty search, which is the inspiration for the publication at the root of t=
his discussion thread.  So certainly we don&#39;t want to imply that novelty se=
arch is the first to explore open-endedness or creativity in evolution (muc=
h of my own work is even in creative evolutionary systems outside novelty s=
earch).  In fact, we view novelty search as a complement to the work in thi=
s area.  Diversity-preservation-mechanisms (such as speciation) and coevolu=
tion also relate to novelty search in various ways.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
However, novel=
ty search is the only generic (i.e. domain-general) evolutionary algorithm =
we know of that explicitly rewards phenotypic novelty and only novelty with=
 no other criteria and no awareness of the objective whatsoever (many such =
prior algorithms combine objective criteria with a drive towards diversity)=
.  To our knowledge it is also the first time that such an open-ended appro=
ach was used to show that many problems considered objective can be transfo=
rmed into non-objective problems that are actually solved better without an=
 objective (which remains a controversial yet useful discussion point).  &lt;b=
r&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
If you would like to share another algorithm that is similar then t=
hat&#39;s great (the book you cited is a survey of many systems, and I don&#39;t kn=
ow of a specific example in that book that works like novelty search).  Of =
course, after four years of publication reviews I would be surprised to see=
 something with the same exact mechanism that our reviewers did not catch, =
but it&#39;s a big world and you never know.  However, I would not be surprised=
 to see many related ideas - of course open-ended evolution and creative ev=
olutionary systems share much of the same inspiration as novelty search.  O=
ur hope was in effect to distill the core essence of such systems into the =
simplest possible heuristic to make its study and applicability as easy and=
 universal as possible.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
It&#39;s probably also useful to note that the=
 motivation for starting this discussion for me was not to argue that novel=
ty search is &quot;superior.&quot;  Rather I think its generality and simplicity make=
 it a useful device for investigating the impact of our field&#39;s longstandin=
g loyalty to objective-driven algorithms and evaluation standards, in parti=
cular in domains that are considered &quot;objective.&quot;  If other approaches also=
 contribute to that discussion then all the better!&lt;br&gt;
